        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> [@yochem](https://github.com/yochem) I mean, yeah, I'm pretty sure everybody will be able to find some workarounds for their use-cases that this change would disturb, but the question is: why? Why overload options with new meanings when adding a dedicated one would be less disruptive, easier to reason about, and consistent with analogous ones (like `foldmethod`)?\n\nI think with what yochem is proposing, `foldmethod` would be analogous to controlling treesitter itself. Like if you wanted to customize which parser to use for a filetype.\n\n> [@Jorenar](https://github.com/Jorenar) why not use a dot to separate the filetypes? Both `'syntax'` and `'filetype'` support setting multiple filetypes/syntaxes using `set ft=dap-disassembly.asm` or `set syntax=treesitter.asm`\n\nI would like this because you could see in one place how Neovim prioritizes which highlighting to use.\n\nWould there be value in making `syntax` a global-local option so that you could define global fallback behaviors, or is that too much?",
            "created_at": "2026-04-20T15:28:52Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/39009#issuecomment-4282140103",
